        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown, deglaze, and build",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a wide pan over high heat. Season the {{beef-chuck}} and brown in batches until deeply coloured on all sides. Transfer to the slow cooker. Add the {{onion}} to the pan and fry for 3 minutes. Add the {{garlic}} and {{tomato-puree}} and cook for 1 minute. Pour in the {{guinness}} and scrape up the browned bits. Add the {{stock-beef}} and {{worcestershire-sauce}} and bring to a simmer. Pour over the beef in the slow cooker. Add the {{carrot}}, {{parsnip}}, {{thyme-fresh}}, {{bay-leaves}}, {{sea-salt-fine}}, and {{black-pepper}}. Cook on low for 8 hours, until the beef is completely tender. Remove the thyme sprigs and bay leaves. Serve with mashed potato.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Dark ales (stout, porter) mellow in the long cook. Pale ales with high hop bitterness intensify. Stick to Guinness or a dark brown ale for this recipe",
              "cause": "Used a pale or hoppy ale rather than a dark one",
              "symptom": "Sauce bitter and harsh"
            },
            {
              "fix": "If the sauce is thin at the end, transfer the liquid to a saucepan and reduce over high heat for 10 minutes before returning it to the pot",
              "cause": "Lid not sealing or too much liquid added",
              "symptom": "Sauce watery rather than thick"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Cut root vegetables into large chunks (4 to 5 cm). They will soften considerably over 8 hours, too small and they disappear",
              "cause": "Cut too small or cooking time too long",
              "symptom": "Vegetables turning to mush by serving time"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Beef and ale stew is a pub and home kitchen standard across Britain, particularly in autumn and winter. The slow cooker version makes it a realistic weekday dinner: built in the morning, ready in the evening, the kitchen smelling of something worthwhile when the household returns. It feeds six comfortably and reheats better than it serves fresh.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
